            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "River Valerio\u2019s story began not in the dense fog of San Francisco, but an hour north in Santa Rosa, on land his Pomo ancestors had inhabited for millennia. Raised by a mother who was a celebrated basket weaver and a father who was a tireless community advocate, River grew up with a dual consciousness: one foot in modern American life, the other firmly planted in the rich soil of his heritage. He saw the world through the stories his elders told, a perspective often starkly at odds with the sanitized history he learned in school.\n\nThis divide became a chasm during a college internship. While studying at UC Berkeley, River worked at a regional museum where he saw priceless Pomo baskets\u2014baskets his own grandmother could have woven\u2014displayed behind glass, stripped of their spirit and context, labeled with cold, anthropological detachment. The experience ignited a quiet fury and a clear purpose. He shifted his focus to Museum Studies, determined to become a storyteller from within the institution, not a critic from the outside.\n\nNow 30, River is an Exhibitions Manager for a prominent San Francisco cultural institution. He has carved out a niche as a vital bridge between historical preservation and contemporary Indigenous voices. His days are a whirlwind of budgets, artist contracts, and layout designs, as he meticulously manages projects that challenge colonial narratives and celebrate living cultures.\n\nHis life is centered in the Inner Richmond. His 3.8-mile bicycle commute is a daily ritual, a quiet meditation as he pedals past Golden Gate Park, the cool air a familiar companion. The $95,000 salary affords him a simple but comfortable life in a city known for its extremes. Evenings are often spent sketching exhibition concepts, meeting friends at a low-key brewery, or attending community events that connect him to the Bay Area\u2019s urban Indian population.\n\nRiver\u2019s connection to San Francisco is deep and complex; he is acutely aware that he lives and works on unceded Ohlone land. This knowledge fuels his ultimate dream: to one day lead a major museum, transforming it into a center for repatriation, collaboration, and truthful reconciliation. For River, it\u2019s about reclaiming the narrative, one correctly labeled basket, one powerful exhibition at a time."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was eight, the dry summer air in Santa Rosa thick with the scent of dust and sun-baked earth. His mother sat on the porch, her hands a blur of practiced motion, weaving damp sedge root into a basket. She paused and let him hold a coil, its texture cool and alive. He understood then, with a child\u2019s clarity, that this was not just a thing, but a story, a prayer given form. That feeling of holding a living history became the sacred benchmark against which he would measure everything.\n\n2.\nAt twenty, the air in the museum was sterile, a stark contrast to the living world he knew. He stood before a glass case, his breath fogging the surface. Inside was a Pomo basket, its pattern a familiar echo of his grandmother\u2019s work. The label, \"Maker Unknown,\" felt like a physical blow. A hot, quiet rage bloomed in his chest\u2014a feeling of profound theft. In that cold, silent hall, his academic path dissolved, replaced by a burning mission: get on the other side of that glass and tell the truth.\n\n3.\nThe opening night for his first major exhibition two years ago was a blur of faces and polite applause. He felt a nervous energy, wondering if the message had landed. Then, an Ohlone elder stood before a display he\u2019d curated. She didn't read his carefully written text. Instead, she lightly touched the frame of a historic photograph and whispered, \"Thank you for bringing our cousin home.\" In that moment, the weight of budgets and deadlines vanished, replaced by a quiet, profound rightness. It was the only validation he needed.\n\n4.\nPedaling home through Golden Gate Park last autumn, a sudden shaft of golden light cut through the cypress trees, illuminating the path. The city noise faded, and he felt the ancient pull of the land beneath the pavement\u2014Yelamu, the Ohlone village that was here first. He felt like both an intruder and a steward, a guest with a solemn responsibility. This daily commute became his ritual acknowledgment, a quiet promise to honor the history buried just beneath the asphalt of his modern life.\n\n5.\nA few months ago, at an Intertribal Friendship House gathering in Oakland, he found himself laughing so hard he could barely breathe over a sarcastic joke someone told about colonial monuments. Surrounded by the easy camaraderie of other urban Indians\u2014Navajo, Lakota, Yuki\u2014the professional weight on his shoulders dissolved. For a few hours, he wasn\u2019t a cultural bridge or a manager. He was just River, part of a resilient and deeply funny community. It was the fuel that made all the other work possible."
